The warning about the protocol not being encrypted is likely related to the blank screen issue. By default, TightVNC uses an unencrypted protocol, which can be a security risk.

To fix this, you can enable encryption on the TightVNC server by adding the following lines to the `~/.vnc/xstartup` file:
```bash
vncConfig = {
  encrypt = "always";
  keyFile = "/home/juan/.vnc/passwd";
};
```
This will enable encryption on the TightVNC server and prompt you to set a password when you connect to the server.

Make sure to restart the TightVNC server after making these changes.

On the VNC client side, you may need to configure the client to use encryption as well. This will depend on the specific VNC client you're using, so you may need to consult the client's documentation for more information.

Once you've enabled encryption on both the server and client, you should be able to connect to the TightVNC server without seeing the blank screen issue.

Note that enabling encryption will add some overhead to the VNC connection, so you may notice a slight performance impact. However, this is a small price to pay for the added security benefits.

